{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9d3fb8d9-bb3f-49e5-b851-395759ad50f5","content":"There's no documentation on this topic in the current repository, but I can answer from general .NET knowledge:\n\n### Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** – run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app so the OS writes a core file on crash.\n\n2. **Check the default crash location** – macOS writes crash logs to:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n3. **Use `/cores/`** – macOS places core files in `/cores/core.<pid>`. Ensure the directory exists and is writable:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Disable SIP restrictions (if needed)** – on modern macOS, System Integrity Protection can prevent core dump generation for some processes. You may need to boot into Recovery Mode and run `csrutil enable --without debug` (use with caution).\n\n5. **Analyze the dump** – open it with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **For .NET-level diagnostics**, you can also use `dotnet-dump analyze` if the core file is available, though NativeAOT support is more limited than CoreCLR.\n\n**Key point:** Since NativeAOT apps don't bundle `createdump`, you rely entirely on the OS-level core dump mechanism (`/cores/`) and macOS crash reports.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e381dcd8-0691-438d-ae4d-95b484386cec","outputTokens":375,"requestId":"AC09:2E3AFD:13DD1F7:16532F8:6A0671B1"},"id":"da18fcfa-983c-4c43-9fe0-2473eca01293","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:07:07.474Z","parentId":"54696bd6-6caa-48a9-9a5c-bbf546ec2ad7"}
